l>When I read articles on this topic, scorepal on android and scorepal on i=
OS are 2 completely different things. The version often referred and spoken=
 of highly of is actually the Android version. It has all the features and =
categories you need for scoring. <br><br>I kept reading glowing reviews or =
recommendations of scorepal and realized that these were actually 2 differe=
nt apps that just happen to have the same name but nowhere equivalent in fe=
atures or design. They do score for BoardGames but whenever it is mentioned=
 and spoken of higjlhly, people are referring to the android version. The i=
OS version on the other hand is just so lite, for standard adding and subtr=
action of numbers, and probably not even by the same developer. <br><br>the=
 iOS version of the app known as Scorepal on the App Store is nowhere on th=
e same level of features, or categories you need to score heavier board gam=
es properly. <br><br>I have been looking for a useful scorekeeping app for =
the apple device but I haven=E2=80=99t found one. I mean even the Apple cal=
culator app really should be showing the list of nUmbers you are typing for=
 an equation rather than blindly emulating a handheld calculator with a sin=
gle line character display. It=E2=80=99s so easy to get calculations wrong =
on a touch screen calculator hen you have series of numbers to be added.</g=
