rkup _ngcontent-ng-c154778266=3D"" itemprop=3D"text" class=3D"clearfix"><gg=
-markup-content><gg-markup-safe-html>For iOS i recently found an app called=
 <strong>ScoreKeeper BACON</strong>. Its just rows and columns and lets you=
 add numbers up very quickly. This is almost similar to a spreadsheet. It m=
ight appear plain, but if you attempt to capture and add sequences of score=
s in a variety of games that are infinitely flexible in how numbers need to=
 be added up, you want something fast and data entry that is not fiddly.<br=
><br>You can switch over to a new scoreboard for a game with pre-filled pag=
es without requiring much more information.<br><br>Is there a real time sha=
red score keeping app? A shared score keeping pad where players log in thro=
ugh a URL, see and add their own numbers (and use the same pad to help them=
 total their own numbers) to the same score keeping session from their own =
phones or web browsers. So players can take charge of their own scores and =
we can all see totals increasing in real time. <img class=3D"emoticon" src=
=3D"https://cf.geekdo-static.com/images/smile.gif" alt=3D""><br><br><br>A n=
ote to all the app game scoring developers on this thread. A lot of the 'be=
autiful and attractive apps, IMHO, look attractive but take so long and fid=
dly to add a score due to their mediocre data entry design that they aren't=
 worth recommending. Why do we look for a scorekeeping app? To record round=
 to round scores only? The app should help us save time.<br><br>A scorekeep=
ing app isn't useful, if all you can do is add ones  together. That's a tal=
ly counter for sports. Boardgames or card game scorekeeping are nothing lik=
e sports. We often have to add long series of numbers, sets, and tokens tog=
ether, then add bonuses into the scoring as well. Then, sometimes, you migh=
t have to add the total amount for all the rounds that you played to determ=
ine the winner.<br><br><strong>App developers should really try to use thei=
r own app. </strong><br><br>- Play four rounds of a game of Lost Cities for=
 2 players, where numbers start with a negative value then increment in lar=
ge sets.  Time how long it takes to add the numbers and bonuses with the ap=
p. Have a person use a notepad and paper to score rounds with individual pl=
ayers.<br><br>- Play a game of Sheriff of Nottingham with 5 players, and to=
tal up the final scores of bonuses, tokens, and see how long that takes to =
count cards, coins, and bonuses round the table for the entire game.<br><br=
>- Play a trick card game and see how your app measures up for helping you =
score a game for 4-5 players, tracking bids, and actual scores. These apps =
will fall flat. A notepad and pencil will probably do the job better and fa=
ster.<br><br>Often a lot of the apps struggle along, with their own fiddlin=
ess to the point, where I've found the fastest most visible way is to take =
a small whiteboard, and get numbers from individual players and help them t=
otal up the bigger numbers on the board, if they are struggling with the fi=
nal count - so that it becomes a group activity.</gg-markup-safe-html><!---=
